Also writing jobs are not freeform. Usually you are given an outline and notes that you have to put in the script, which will then be revised and given more notes on what to put in the script. You're not really a writer, you're more of a guy who fills in the blanks between scenes that someone better paid than you are is excited to do. Hell, you will be locked in a windowless room for a few weeks and then you leave. You will never get to see them actually working out your scripts because you turn it in so early that you are off onto the next job by the time they are filming, provided they are filming anywhere near you.

Keep in mind this is entirely from the perspective of being hired off the street or Twitter. That your ability or vision is entirely inconsequential to the product you are producing. Other times writers are have some relationship with the directors or actors or producers and its more cooperative.
